{
  "metadata": {
    "anchor_id": "member_c",
    "description": "58-year-old female, HMO plan. Chronic disease management (Type 2 Diabetes + Hypertension) with formulary conflict — Ozempic denied for step therapy, Jardiance fails, Ozempic approved. Jan–Dec 2025 longitudinal narrative.",
    "created": "2026-03-06",
    "narrative_summary": "Maria Santos is a 58-year-old woman in Miami managing Type 2 Diabetes and Hypertension on an HMO plan. In January 2025 her PCP found her A1C at 7.8% (above target) and referred her to an endocrinologist. The endocrinologist recommended switching from Metformin to Ozempic, but the prior auth was denied — the plan requires step therapy (must fail on Jardiance first). Maria called member services, frustrated. She started Jardiance but developed UTIs as a side effect. After documenting treatment failure, the endocrinologist resubmitted the Ozempic auth and it was approved. Maria switched to Ozempic and by September her A1C dropped to 6.9% (at target). She sent a thank-you message to the care team. The year concluded with a diabetic retinopathy screening and annual wellness visit with stable metrics."
  },

